snippet.textDisplay:
Not sure on the SuoerDuty trucks, but on the F150 the only steel part is the dash panle/firewall. Ford used "self piercing" rivets to assemble most of the aluminum components. The rivets install quickly (via a robot which pushes the hardened rivet straight through the aluminum with no pre-drilled hole), has zero "cure" time (unlike adhesive) and cost less than that fancy panel adhesive.
Where did you get your rivets ? Those are not just "hardware store" rivets !
DO NOT DRILL/TAP/THREAD BOLTS WHERE THERE WAS RIVETS ! The bolts will pull out the threads. The rivets give a lot more surface area on the backside.

snippet.textDisplay:
I guarantee these guys dont have the $20k rivit gun system we have to have to be a ford aluminum certified collision repair shop. And I know they definitely dont have the $150k frame machine. Or the clean room to do it. Theres alot more to properly repairing these trucks than an old steel truck. Just because you can buy a bunch of parts and kinda make it fit back together doesn't mean it's fixed correctly. But it isnt my life in jeopardy with this repair so what do I care...
Theres a reason us collision structural repair techs have to take so many classes, and certifications and make the big bucks. If our repair fails someone could die. Theses new cars are nothing like the cars we had even 10 or 15 years ago.
